SOLID is a set of five object-oriented design principles used to create clean, maintainable, scalable, and loosely coupled software.
These principles help developers write code that is easy to understand, test, and modify.
SRP(Single Responsibility Principle) → SRP ensures a class has a single responsibility
OCP(Open Closed Principle) → OCP allows adding new features without modifying existing code
LSP(Open Closed Principle) → Child Replaces Parent Safely
ISP(Interface Segregation Principle) → Don't implement methods you don't use
DIP(Dependency Inversion Principle) → Depend on interfaces, not implementations

1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
Single Responsibility Principle states that a class should have only one responsibility and one reason to change.
Each class should focus on a single business function rather than handling multiple tasks.
This improves code readability, maintainability, and testability.
In Spring Boot, Controller, Service, and Repository layers are common examples of SRP.
This principle helps create clean and well-organized code.

2. Open Closed Principle (OCP)
Open Closed Principle states that software components should be open for extension but closed for modification.
New functionality should be added without changing existing, tested code.
This reduces the risk of introducing bugs into working functionality.
OCP is commonly achieved using interfaces, inheritance, and polymorphism.
It makes applications more flexible and scalable when new requirements arise.
For example, adding a new payment method should require creating a new class instead of modifying existing payment logic.
This principle helps in building maintainable applications.

3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
Liskov Substitution Principle states that a child class should be able to replace its parent class without affecting the flow of the application.
A subclass must preserve the behavior and expectations defined by the parent class.
Any code that works with the parent class should also work correctly with its child classes.
LSP encourages proper inheritance design and class hierarchies.

4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Interface Segregation Principle states that a class should not be forced to implement methods that it does not use.
Large and general-purpose interfaces should be divided into smaller, more specific interfaces.
This allows classes to implement only the functionality relevant to them.
ISP reduces unnecessary dependencies and avoids empty or unsupported method implementations.

5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Dependency Inversion Principle states that high-level modules should not depend on low-level modules; both should depend on abstractions.
Classes should depend on interfaces rather than concrete implementations.
This reduces tight coupling between components and increases flexibility.
Changes in implementation details do not affect business logic when abstractions are used.
DIP is commonly implemented through Dependency Injection in Spring Boot.